COMEDIAN and author Trevor Noah continues to fly Mzansi’s flag abroad. He’s been announced as the host of the Grammy Awards, making him the first South African to host the prestigious awards ceremony. Speaking to Variety, the award-winning comedian said he is thrilled about hosting the Grammys. “Despite the fact that I’m extremely disappointed that the Grammys have refused to have me sing or be nominated for Best Pop Album, I’m thrilled to be hosting this auspicious event,” he said. ALSO READ | DRINK TO THAT Trevor, who is a former Grammy nominee, said: “I think as a one-time Grammy nominee, I’m the best person to provide a shoulder to all the amazing artists who don’t win on the night because I too know the pain of not winning the award! (This is a metaphorical shoulder, I’m not trying to catch corona.) See you at the 63rd Grammys!” The 63rd annual Grammy Awards will be held next year on 31 January. A post shared by Trevor Noah (@trevornoah) 